Reasoning: The paper deals with Binary Search Trees (BSTs) and their algorithms, which are fundamental data structures in computer science. The paper presents a general method for de-amortizing BST algorithms, which is a topic that falls under the category of data structure design and analysis. Therefore, the most likely arXiv CS sub-category for this paper is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). Additionally, the paper discusses the performance of the transformed BSTs in terms of time complexity, which is a topic that falls under the category of algorithm analysis. Therefore, cs.AL (Algorithms) is also a likely sub-category. The paper also mentions the scanning theorem, static optimality theorem, static finger theorem, and working set theorem, which are topics related to information theory and coding theory. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) is another likely sub-category. The paper also mentions the concept of competitiveness, which is a topic related to distributed computing and game theory. Therefore, cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) is another likely sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the performance of BST algorithms in worst-case scenarios, which is a topic related to computational complexity theory. Therefore, cs.CC (Computational Complexity) is another likely sub-category.
